'''Anthony Michael Gordon''' (born 24 February 2001) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays primarily as a [[Winger (association football)|winger]] for [[Premier League]] club [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] and the [[England national football team|England national team]]. He will join {{Spanish football updater|Barcelona}} club [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] on 1 July 2026.

Gordon began his professional career with [[Everton F.C.|Everton]], making his senior debut in December 2017 in a [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] match, before joining [[Newcastle United]] in 2023. In 2026, he moved to Barcelona for £69.3 million.

==Early life==
Anthony Michael Gordon<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/1697050 |title=Premier League clubs publish 2019/20 retained lists |publisher=Premier League |date=26 June 2020 |access-date=9 July 2020 |archive-date=24 May 2023 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230524201938/https://www.premierleague.com/news/1697050 |url-status=live }}</ref> was born on 24 February 2001<ref name="PremProfile"/> in [[Liverpool]], Merseyside.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.evertonfc.com/news/1724357/anthony-gordon-exclusive-being-a-good-person-is-more-important-than-anything | title=Anthony Gordon Exclusive: 'Being a Good Person is More Important Than Anything' | access-date=3 November 2023 | archive-date=26 June 2024 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240626115434/https://www.evertonfc.com/news/1724357/anthony-gordon-exclusive-being-a-good-person-is-more-important-than-anything | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.evertonfc.com/news/1577805/gordon-sets-target-after-best-day-of-his-life |title=Gordon sets target after 'best day of his life' |first=Howard |last=Frost |publisher=Everton F.C. |date=19 January 2020 |access-date=26 August 2022 |archive-date=25 August 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220825231457/https://www.evertonfc.com/news/1577805/gordon-sets-target-after-best-day-of-his-life |url-status=live }}</ref> He is of Irish and Scottish descent.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/anthony-gordon-england-scotland-euro-2024-b2516303.html |title=Anthony Gordon reveals why he chose England over Scotland |first=Mark |last=Mann-Bryans |newspaper=The Independent |location=London |date=21 March 2024 |access-date=17 September 2024}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Everton===
[[File:Anthony Gordon (cropped).jpg|thumb|150px|Gordon playing for Everton in 2021]]
Gordon joined [[Everton F.C.|Everton]] as an 11-year-old<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.evertonfc.com/news/2017/12/07/copy-of-who-are-evertons-debutants |title=Who Are Everton's Five Debutants? |publisher=Everton F.C. |date=7 December 2017 |access-date=8 December 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171209045607/http://www.evertonfc.com/news/2017/12/07/copy-of-who-are-evertons-debutants |archive-date=9 December 2017}}</ref> following his release from [[Liverpool F.C. Reserves and Academy|Liverpool's Academy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://talksport.com/football/1091864/everton-anthony-gordon-released-liverpool-quadruple-premier-league-relegation/|title=Gordon was released by Liverpool and could end Reds' quadruple dream for Everton|first=Joe|last=Brophy|date=22 April 2022|accessdate=22 April 2022|website=TalkSport|archive-date=22 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220422143945/https://talksport.com/football/1091864/everton-anthony-gordon-released-liverpool-quadruple-premier-league-relegation/|url-status=live}}</ref> On 6 December 2017, Gordon was named in Everton's first-team squad for the [[UEFA Europa League|Europa League]] match away to [[Apollon Limassol]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/everton-squad-apollon-limassol-europa-14003917|title=Everton squad for Apollon Limassol Europa League match includes eight possible debutants|first=Phil|last=Kirkbride|date=6 December 2017|accessdate=7 December 2017|website=Liverpool Echo|archive-date=21 September 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200921072407/https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/everton-squad-apollon-limassol-europa-14003917|url-status=live}}</ref> A day later, he made his first-team debut in the fixture, coming on as an 88th-minute substitute in a 3–0 win.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2017/12/07/europe/uefa-cup/apollon-limassol/everton-football-club/2580366/?ICID=HP_MS_01_08 |title=APOLLON VS. EVERTON 0–3 |access-date=7 December 2017 |website=Soccerway |archive-date=16 September 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180916213508/https://int.soccerway.com/matches/2017/12/07/europe/uefa-cup/apollon-limassol/everton-football-club/2580366/?ICID=HP_MS_01_08 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Begley |first1=Emlyn |title=Apollon Limassol 0 Everton 3 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42253361 |website=BBC Sport |access-date=8 December 2017 |date=7 December 2017 |archive-date=9 November 2022 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20221109001148/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/42253361 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 18 January 2020, Gordon made his [[Premier League]] debut coming on as a substitute for [[Bernard (footballer)|Bernard]] in a 1–1 draw with [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]]. On 26 June, he received his first Premier League start in a 0–0 draw with Liverpool.<ref name="PNE">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55896334|title=Preston sign Stoke's Lindsay, Liverpool's Van den Berg & Everton's Gordon on loan|newspaper=BBC Sport|date=2 February 2021|access-date=14 July 2023|archive-date=13 July 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230713121752/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/55896334|url-status=live}}</ref> On 1 September, Gordon signed a new five-year contract with Everton.<ref>{{Cite news |date=1 September 2020 |title=Anthony Gordon: Everton midfielder signs new five-year deal |website=BBC Sport |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53981857 |access-date=1 September 2020 |archive-date=22 April 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210422163237/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/53981857 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 1 February 2021, Gordon joined [[EFL Championship|Championship]] club [[Preston North End F.C.|Preston North End]] on loan for the remainder of the 2020–21 season.<ref name="PNE"/><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.pnefc.net/news/2021/february/anthony-gordon-beats-the-deadline-to-join-from-everton/ |title=Anthony Gordon Beats The Deadline To Join From Everton |publisher=Preston North End F.C. |date=1 February 2021 |access-date=1 February 2021 |archive-date=20 September 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210920230105/https://www.pnefc.net/news/2021/february/anthony-gordon-beats-the-deadline-to-join-from-everton/ |url-status=live }}</ref> Five days later, he made his debut for Preston, being included in the starting line-up for a 2–1 home league defeat by [[Rotherham United F.C.|Rotherham United]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/55866861 |title=Preston North End 1–2 Rotherham United: Millers battle to win over Preston |website=BBC Sport |date=6 February 2021 |access-date=15 February 2021 |archive-date=8 February 2021 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210208064644/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/55866861 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 16 December, Gordon registered his first assist for Everton, as [[Jarrad Branthwaite]] scored from his free-kick in a 1–1 draw with [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59589156|title=Chelsea 1–1 Everton|website=BBC Sport|first=Michael|last=Emons|date=16 December 2021|access-date=16 August 2023|archive-date=16 August 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230816174724/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59589156|url-status=live}}</ref> On 2 January 2022, he scored his first goals for the ''Toffees'' in a 3–2 loss to [[Brighton & Hove Albion F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59792556|title=Everton 2–3 Brighton & Hove Albion|website=BBC Sport|first=Harry|last=Poole|date=2 January 2022|access-date=16 August 2023|archive-date=8 April 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220408074204/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59792556|url-status=live}}</ref> On 12 February, in a 3–0 win over [[Leeds United F.C.|Leeds United]], he assisted [[Michael Keane (footballer, born 1993)|Michael Keane]] for Everton's second goal, before scoring their third in the second half.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60269090|title=Everton 3–0 Leeds United|website=BBC Sport|first=Emma|last=Sanders|date=12 February 2022|access-date=16 August 2023|archive-date=15 August 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220815115359/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60269090|url-status=live}}</ref> On 9 April, Gordon scored the only goal of the game in a win over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60963791|title=Everton 1–0 Manchester United|website=BBC Sport|first=Phil|last=McNulty|author-link=Phil McNulty|date=9 April 2022|access-date=16 August 2023|archive-date=22 August 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220822013058/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/60963791|url-status=live}}</ref> In May, he was named Young Player of the Year by the senior team and the club's supporters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.evertonfc.com/news/2634469/pickford-and-gordon-scoop-everton-awards|title=Pickford And Gordon Scoop Everton Awards|publisher=Everton F.C.|date=25 May 2022|access-date=16 August 2023|archive-date=25 May 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220525153024/https://www.evertonfc.com/news/2634469/pickford-and-gordon-scoop-everton-awards|url-status=live}}</ref> During the 2022 summer transfer window, he was linked with Chelsea.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12679631/anthony-gordon-chelsea-prepared-to-pay-up-to-60m-for-everton-forward|title=Anthony Gordon: Chelsea prepared to pay up to £60m for Everton forward|website=Sky Sports|date=25 August 2022|access-date=16 August 2023|archive-date=26 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240626115508/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12679631/anthony-gordon-chelsea-prepared-to-pay-up-to-60m-for-everton-forward|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62732848|title=Everton: Anthony Gordon transfer deadline has passed, says Frank Lampard|website=BBC Sport|first=Alistair|last=Magowan|date=30 August 2022|access-date=16 August 2023|archive-date=16 August 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230816173219/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62732848|url-status=live}}</ref>

Gordon scored his first goals of [[2022–23 Everton F.C. season|the season]] in back-to-back matches against [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]] and Leeds United.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62614442|title=Brentford 1–0 Everton|website=BBC Sport|date=27 August 2022|access-date=16 August 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/62641732|title=Leeds United 1–1 Everton|website=BBC Sport|first=Alistair|last=Magowan|date=30 August 2022|access-date=16 August 2023}}</ref> He was suspended for the match against [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]], because of yellow card accumulation,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/everton-suffer-anthony-gordon-blow-25220612|title=Everton suffer Anthony Gordon blow for Tottenham Hotspur trip|work=Liverpool Echo|first=Chris|last=Beesley|date=10 October 2022}}</ref> and returned in a 1–0 defeat to [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]]. He had a scuffle with [[Kieran Trippier]], which led to a confrontation with [[Fabian Schär]], resulting in both players getting booked.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/63224225|title=Newcastle 1–0 Everton|website=BBC Sport|first=Alistair|last=Magowan|date=25 August 2022|access-date=16 August 2023}}</ref> (The three players were reunited soon after his transfer to Newcastle, which was noted for Gordon's awkward interaction with Schär.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://talksport.com/football/1319111/anthony-gordon-joke-fabian-schar-newcastle-transfer-everton/|title=Anthony Gordon jokingly told he'll have to earn Fabian Schar's protection after first meeting with Newcastle teammate since on-pitch scuffle last October|work=TalkSport|first=Lee|last=Davey|date=31 January 2023|access-date=16 August 2023|archive-date=16 August 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230816173217/https://talksport.com/football/1319111/anthony-gordon-joke-fabian-schar-newcastle-transfer-everton/|url-status=live}}</ref>) In the next match, he scored Everton's second goal in a 3–0 win over [[Crystal Palace F.C.|Crystal Palace]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/63267159|title=Everton 3–0 Crystal Palace|website=BBC Sport|first=Emma|last=Sanders|date=22 October 2022|access-date=16 August 2023|archive-date=26 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240626120444/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/63267159|url-status=live}}</ref> Illness kept him out for three matches, and in what turned out to be his last appearance for the ''Toffees'', he came on as a 69th-minute substitute against [[Southampton F.C.|Southampton]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64195234|title=Everton 1–2 Southampton|website=BBC Sport|first=Gary|last=Rose|date=30 August 2022|access-date=16 August 2023|archive-date=21 January 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230121185530/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64195234|url-status=live}}</ref> After the match, he and [[Yerry Mina]] were harassed by a small section of Everton supporters.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12679631/anthony-gordon-chelsea-prepared-to-pay-up-to-60m-for-everton-forward|title=Everton fans roadblock Anthony Gordon and shout 'get out of our club' while Yerry Mina gets out of car to confront supporters who demand 'passion' after Southampton defeat|work=TalkSport|first=Connor|last=Andrews|date=15 January 2022|access-date=16 August 2023|archive-date=26 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240626115508/https://www.skysports.com/football/news/11095/12679631/anthony-gordon-chelsea-prepared-to-pay-up-to-60m-for-everton-forward|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/articles/c1dzkm44nedo|title='We understand the passion' – Lampard on fans confronting players|website=BBC Sport|date=19 January 2023|access-date=16 August 2023|archive-date=26 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240626120443/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/articles/c1dzkm44nedo|url-status=live}}</ref> During the January transfer window, Sky Sports reported that Gordon had failed to show up to training in order to force a move away from the club to fellow Premier League club [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.skysports.com/football/news/12040/12795973/anthony-gordon-newcastle-hold-talks-with-everton-as-winger-fails-to-turn-up-to-training-for-third-consecutive-day|title=Anthony Gordon: Newcastle hold talks with Everton as winger fails to turn up to training for third consecutive day|website=Sky Sports}}</ref> Gordon later expressed he had been disappointed by the curt manner that Everton announced his departure, and stated that he "was a massive part in keeping the club up" the previous season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64919398|title=Anthony Gordon says lack of 'credit' from Everton hurt him after Newcastle move|website=BBC Sport|date=10 March 2023|access-date=10 March 2023|archive-date=26 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240626120010/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/64919398|url-status=live}}</ref>

===Newcastle United===
[[File:Anthony Elanga and Anthony Gordon 24052026 (1).jpg|thumb|200px|Gordon (right) warming up for Newcastle United in 2026]]
On 29 January 2023, Gordon joined [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on a long-term contract, having submitted a formal transfer request to previous club [[Everton F.C.|Everton]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.evertonfc.com/news/2023/january/29/gordon-leaves-everton/ |title=Gordon Leaves Everton |publisher=Everton F.C. |date=29 January 2023 |access-date=29 January 2023}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newcastleunited.com/en/news/newcastle-united-sign-anthony-gordon |title=Newcastle United sign Anthony Gordon |publisher=Newcastle United F.C. |date=29 January 2023 |access-date=29 January 2023}}</ref> The [[transfer fee]] reported by [[BBC Sport]] was an initial £40&nbsp;million, potentially rising to £45&nbsp;million in add-ons.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64441380 |title=Anthony Gordon: Newcastle sign Everton forward in £45m deal |website=BBC Sport |date=29 January 2023 |access-date=29 January 2023}}</ref> He made his debut on 4 February as a 69th-minute substitute in a 1–1 draw at home to [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64436129 |title=Newcastle United 1–1 West Ham United |first=Neil |last=Johnston |website=BBC Sport |date=4 February 2023 |access-date=4 February 2023}}</ref> On 4 March, Gordon was named in the starting line-up for the first time in a 2–0 loss to [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]], but was taken off in the 62nd minute,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/64768044|title=Manchester City 2–0 Newcastle United|website=BBC Sport|first=Chris|last=Bevan|date=4 March 2023|access-date=16 August 2023}}</ref> and an ankle injury would see him miss the next two matches.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4300265/2023/03/12/anthony-gordon-ankle-injury/|title=Anthony Gordon set to miss Newcastle's next two matches with ankle injury|work=The Athletic|first=Chris|last=Waugh|date=12 March 2023|access-date=16 August 2023|archive-date=26 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240626120446/https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/4300265/2023/03/12/anthony-gordon-ankle-injury/|url-status=live}}</ref> After making his return in a 2–0 win over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], he was mainly used as a substitute. On 8 April, against [[Brentford F.C.|Brentford]], he came on at half-time, but had the ignominy of being subbed off.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65145674|title=Brentford 1–2 Newcastle United|website=BBC Sport|first=Sam|last=Drury|date=14 April 2023|access-date=16 August 2023}}</ref> He reacted angrily to manager [[Eddie Howe]], who later explained that Gordon had come off as a precaution because of his ankle injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65275310|title=Anthony Gordon: Newcastle boss Eddie Howe has 'no issue' with winger's angry reaction to being substituted|website=BBC Sport|first=Chris|last=Bevan|date=14 April 2023|access-date=16 August 2023|archive-date=16 August 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230816173223/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65275310|url-status=live}}</ref> Expecting a hostile reception upon his return to [[Goodison Park]] on 27 April,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65398627|title=Newcastle: Eddie Howe urges Anthony Gordon to shut out the noise on Everton return|website=BBC Sport|first=Harry|last=De Cosemo|date=26 April 2023|access-date=16 August 2023|archive-date=26 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240626120446/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65398627|url-status=live}}</ref> his contribution ended up being minimal, with the game already won as Newcastle were 4–1 up.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65332145|title=Everton 1–4 Newcastle United|website=BBC Sport|first=Shamoon|last=Hafez|date=27 April 2023|access-date=16 August 2023|archive-date=26 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240626120448/https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/65332145|url-status=live}}</ref> On 28 May, Gordon scored his first goal for the club in a 1–1 draw with [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] on the final day of the [[2022–23 Newcastle United F.C. season|2022–23 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65661808|title=Chelsea 1–1 Newcastle United|website=BBC Sport|first=Harry|last=De Cosemo|date=28 May 2023|access-date=16 August 2023}}</ref>

On 12 August, Gordon assisted [[Sandro Tonali]] for the opening goal in a 5–1 win over [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]] in Newcastle's first game of the [[2023–24 Newcastle United F.C. season|2023–24 season]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66413644|title=Newcastle United 5–1 Aston Villa|website=BBC Sport|first=Chris|last=Bertram|date=12 August 2023|access-date=16 August 2023}}</ref>
On 27 August 2023, Gordon scored his first home goal for Newcastle in a 2–1 defeat against boyhood club [[Liverpool FC|Liverpool]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://liverpooloffside.sbnation.com/2023/8/27/23847887/newcastle-united-1-liverpool-fc-2-epl-2023-result-recap-darwin-nunez-anthony-gordon-virgil-van-dijk|title=Newcastle 1, Liverpool 2 – Match Recap: New Rules, Darwin To The Rescue|website=www.liverpooloffside.sbnation.com|date=27 August 2023|access-date=27 August 2023|archive-date=26 June 2024|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240626120223/https://liverpooloffside.sbnation.com/2023/8/27/23847887/newcastle-united-1-liverpool-fc-2-epl-2023-result-recap-darwin-nunez-anthony-gordon-virgil-van-dijk|url-status=live}}</ref> Gordon continued his fine form over the course of the season, earning him Newcastle United's Player of the Season awards.<ref name="POTS2324"/>
Although he could not play in the final due to suspension, Anthony Gordon scored goals in both legs of the 2025 EFL Cup semi-final victory against Arsenal, helping the team to become the first Newcastle United side to win a major domestic trophy in 70 years.<ref>{{cite web |title=Liverpool 1–2 Newcastle United |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c62zl58dg8qt |website=BBC Football |access-date=20 March 2025}}</ref>

On 25 August, Gordon became the second Premier League player since [[Mason Holgate]] to be sent off in each of the past three seasons when he committed a dangerous tackle on [[Virgil van Dijk]] after referee [[Simon Hooper]] viewed the VAR monitor when the yellow card decision was overturned. In his absence, Newcastle went on to suffer a late 3–2 defeat to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite web |title= Newcastle United 2–3 Liverpool|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c776m8l58j8t |website=BBC Football |access-date=26 August 2025}}</ref> Later that year, on 21 October, he scored in Newcastle's 3–0 home win over [[S.L. Benfica|Benfica]] in the [[UEFA Champions League|Champions League]], becoming the first Newcastle player to score in three consecutive matches in the competition.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Kelly |first=Ciaran |date=2025-10-21 |title=How Newcastle's other forwards stepped up in Champions League |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cjw92q97gllo |access-date=2025-10-22 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref>

On 18 February 2026, Gordon scored four goals in an 6–1 win over [[Qarabağ FK|Qarabağ]] in the [[2025–26 UEFA Champions League knockout phase|UEFA Champions League play-offs]], marking his first senior hat-trick and becoming the third Newcastle player to score a [[List of UEFA Champions League hat-tricks|hat-trick]] in the Champions League, alongside [[Faustino Asprilla]] and [[Alan Shearer]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.newcastleunited.com/en/news/best-reaction-from-qarabag-fk-win-as-anthony-gordon-and-newcastle-united |title=Best reaction from Qarabağ FK win as Anthony Gordon and Newcastle United break records |publisher=Newcastle United F.C. |date=18 February 2026 }}</ref> He also became the first Newcastle player to score four goals in a single match in a European competition.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Qarabağ vs Newcastle United: Champions League play-off first leg |url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cev7g8jwn9pt |access-date=2026-02-18 |website=BBC Sport |language=en-GB}}</ref> In addition, he became only the second English player to score at least 10 goals in a single UEFA Champions League campaign, following [[Harry Kane]], who achieved the feat in the 2024–25 season.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.iffhs.com/posts/4940 |title=GAME OF RECORDS |publisher=IFFHS |date=19 February 2026 }}</ref>

===Barcelona===
On 29 May 2026, Gordon joined [[La Liga]] club [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] on a five-year contract which starts from 1 July 2026.<ref>{{cite web |title=Anthony Gordon becomes an FC Barcelona player |url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/news/4511134/anthony-gordon-becomes-an-fc-barcelona-player |publisher=[[FC Barcelona]] |access-date=29 May 2026 |date=29 May 2026}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Anthony Gordon signs for Barcelona {{!}} NUFC |url=https://www.newcastleunited.com/en/news/anthony-gordon-signs-for-barcelona |access-date=2026-05-30 |publisher=Newcastle United F.C. |language=en}}</ref> The deal was reportedly worth €80m (approximately £69.3 million).<ref>{{cite web |last=Ornstein |first=David |last2=Ballús |first2=Pol |title=Barcelona agree €80m deal with Newcastle for Anthony Gordon |url=https://www.nytimes.com/athletic/6431483/2026/05/27/anthony-gordon-barcelona-newcastle-transfer/ |publisher=The Athletic |access-date=29 May 2026 |date=29 May 2026}}</ref>

==International career==

=== Youth career ===
Having represented his country at U18 and U19 level, Gordon made his debut for the [[England national under-20 football team|England under-20s]] during a 2–0 victory over [[Wales national under-20 football team|Wales]] at [[St George's Park National Football Centre|St George's Park]] on 13 October 2020.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thefa.com/news/2020/oct/13/england-mu20s-wales-report-131020 |title=Two quickfire goals in the first half seal win for Lee Carsley's young Lions at SGP |first=Nicholas |last=Veevers |publisher=The Football Association |date=13 October 2020 |access-date=13 October 2020 |archive-date=18 October 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20201018011546/https://www.thefa.com/news/2020/oct/13/england-mu20s-wales-report-131020 |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 5 November 2021, Gordon received his first call up for the [[England national under-21 football team|England under-21s]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2021/Nov/05/england-mens-under-21-squad-announced-november-20211105 |title=Fleetwood Town and Everton youngsters receive maiden England MU21s call-ups |first=Frank |last=Smith |publisher=The Football Association |date=5 November 2021 |access-date=8 November 2021}}</ref> and scored twice on his debut, a 3–1 victory over [[Czech Republic national under-21 football team|Czech Republic]] at [[Turf Moor]] in [[2023 UEFA European Under-21 Championship qualification]] on 11 November 2021.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2021/Nov/11/england-mens-under-21s-czech-republic-match-report-20211111 |title=England MU21s secure crucial Euro qualifying victory |first=Paul |last=Eddison |publisher=The Football Association |date=11 November 2021 |access-date=12 November 2021 |archive-date=26 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240626120450/https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2021/Nov/11/england-mens-under-21s-czech-republic-match-report-20211111 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59254061|title=England U21 3–1 Czech Republic U21|website=BBC Sport|date=11 November 2021|access-date=14 July 2023|archive-date=14 July 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230714112954/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/59254061|url-status=live}}</ref>

On 14 June 2023, Gordon was included in the England squad for the [[2023 UEFA European Under-21 Championship]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2023/Jun/14/england-mens-under-21s-squad-named-for-uefa-u21-euro-finals-20231406|title=England MU21s squad named for EURO Finals|first=Nicholas|last=Veevers|publisher=England Football|date=14 June 2023|access-date=26 June 2023|archive-date=10 July 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230710023747/https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2023/Jun/14/england-mens-under-21s-squad-named-for-uefa-u21-euro-finals-20231406|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65903299|title=England Under-21s: Gibbs-White, Smith Rowe & Gordon in but Lewis left out|website=BBC Sport|date=14 June 2023|access-date=14 July 2023|archive-date=11 July 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230711100448/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/65903299|url-status=live}}</ref> He scored during a group stage victory over [[Israel national under-21 football team|Israel]] and also recorded the only goal of the quarter-final against [[Portugal national under-21 football team|Portugal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66013874|title=England U21 2–0 Israel U21|first=Alex|last=Howell|date=25 June 2023|accessdate=14 July 2023|website=BBC Sport|archive-date=11 July 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230711202503/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66013874|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66069220|title=England U21 1–0 Portugal U21|first=Alex|last=Howell|date=2 July 2023|accessdate=14 July 2023|website=BBC Sport|archive-date=11 July 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230711202505/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66069220|url-status=live}}</ref> On 8 July 2023, Gordon started in the [[2023 UEFA European Under-21 Championship final|final]] as England beat [[Spain national under-21 football team|Spain]] to lift the trophy.<ref name="u21">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66127349|title=England beat Spain to win Euro U21 Championship|first=Alex|last=Howell|website=BBC Sport|date=8 July 2023|accessdate=8 July 2023|archive-date=7 July 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230707222140/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/66127349|url-status=live}}</ref> Gordon was named Player of the Tournament and also chosen in the Team of the Tournament.<ref name="pott">{{cite news |url=https://www.uefa.com/under21/news/0283-1871d669de39-41d3412d964f-1000--england-s-anthony-gordon-named-2023-under-21-euro-player-of/|title=England's Anthony Gordon named 2023 Under-21 EURO Player of the Tournament {{!}} Under-21|newspaper=UEFA|date=8 July 2023|access-date=8 July 2023}}</ref><ref name="tott">{{cite news|url=https://www.uefa.com/under21/news/0283-1876f534fb25-e069a027749d-1000--team-of-the-tournament/|title=2023 Under-21 EURO Team of the Tournament|newspaper=UEFA|date=11 July 2023|access-date=14 July 2023|archive-date=2 September 2023|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20230902105730/https://www.uefa.com/under21/news/0283-1876f534fb25-e069a027749d-1000--team-of-the-tournament/|url-status=live}}</ref>

=== Senior career ===
Gordon received his first call up for the [[England national football team|England senior squad]] in March 2024 for [[Friendly (association football)|friendlies]] against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]] and [[Belgium national football team|Belgium]].<ref>{{cite news |title=England squad: Anthony Gordon and Jarrad Branthwaite receive first call-ups |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68564319 |website=BBC Sport |date=14 March 2024 |access-date=14 March 2024 |archive-date=14 March 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240314170642/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68564319 |url-status=live }}</ref> He made his debut on 23 March when starting England's 1–0 defeat to Brazil at [[Wembley Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68647860 |title=England 0–1 Brazil |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=23 March 2024 |access-date=23 March 2024 |archive-date=23 March 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240323173836/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/68647860 |url-status=live }}</ref> He was named in England's 26-man squad for [[UEFA Euro 2024]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cv22menk7dno |title=Eze & Wharton named in England squad for Euro 2024 |website=BBC Sport |date=6 June 2024 |access-date=6 June 2024 |archive-date=6 June 2024 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20240606170808/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/articles/cv22menk7dno |url-status=live }}</ref>

On 17 November 2024, Gordon scored his first senior international goal in a 5–0 [[2024–25 UEFA Nations League B|UEFA Nations League]] victory against the [[Republic of Ireland national football team|Republic of Ireland]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=McNulty |first1=Phil |title=England 5–0 Republic of Ireland: Hosts score five in second half to earn Nations League promotion |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/live/c98envjpj72t |website=BBC Sport |access-date=17 November 2024 |date=17 November 2024}}</ref>

In May 2026, Gordon was named to the 26-man squad to represent England in the [[2026 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Veevers |first=Nicholas |url=https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2026/May/22/england-mens-world-cup-2026-squad-named-by-thomas-tuchel-20262205 |title=Three Lions Come Together for World Cup |publisher=[[The Football Association]] |date=May 22, 2026 |access-date=May 22, 2026 |archive-date=May 22, 2026 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20260522101615/https://www.englandfootball.com/articles/2026/May/22/england-mens-world-cup-2026-squad-named-by-thomas-tuchel-20262205 |url-status=live}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Gordon is in a relationship with Annie Keating. He became a father in 2023.<ref>{{cite web | last=Scurr | first=Dominic | title=The 'risky' Newcastle United transfer Dan Ashworth & PIF 'fought' to secure | website=Shields Gazette | date=7 February 2023 | url=https://www.shieldsgazette.com/sport/football/newcastle-united/the-risky-newcastle-united-transfer-dan-ashworth-pif-fought-to-secure-4017507 | access-date=18 February 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/anthony-gordon-newcastle-united-palace-27958394.amp | title=Anthony Gordon's goal message will strike fear into Premier League rivals | date=21 October 2023 | access-date=3 November 2023 | archive-date=3 November 2023 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231103102744/https://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/anthony-gordon-newcastle-united-palace-27958394.amp | url-status=live }}</ref>

Gordon has spoken about the importance of books in driving his success, with ''The Art of Winning'' by former [[New Zealand national rugby union team|New Zealand]] [[Rugby union|rugby]] player [[Dan Carter]] cited as one of his favourites.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hytner |first1=David |title=Gordon straight back in saddle to help England move through the gears |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/article/2024/jun/28/gordon-straight-back-in-saddle-to-help-england-move-through-the-gears |work=The Guardian |date=28 June 2024 |access-date=25 October 2024}}</ref>

